How do Air Pollutants Affect PM2.5 in NY State

Yutong_Wu

11/28/2019

1. Project Overview

Air pollution is one of the most significant environmental problem in New York and causes more than 3000 death yearly. (according to [NYC Health] (https://www1.nyc.gov/assets/doh/downloads/pdf/eode/eode-air-quality-impact.pdf))

This project aims to evaluate the air quality (measured by pm2.5) by different counties in NY state and investigate how air pollutant (CO, NO2, O3, SO2) contribute to the air pollution (pm2.5).

2. Predict Air Quality and Predictors Analysis

The data is downloaded from [EPA] (https://www.epa.gov/outdoor-air-quality-data/download-daily-data). We use daily data in 2018.

Read the csv file of the 5 pollutants data.

data_PM <- read.csv (file = "NY_air_Data/pm2.5_2018.csv")
data_NO2 <- read.csv (file = "NY_air_Data/no2_2018.csv")
data_CO <- read.csv (file = "NY_air_Data/co_2018.csv")
data_SO2 <- read.csv (file = "NY_air_Data/so2_2018.csv")
data_O3 <- read.csv (file = "NY_air_Data/o3_2018.csv")

head (data_PM)

Select the columns that we need.

data_pm2.5 <- data_PM %>%
  select (Date, daily.pm2.5 = Daily.Mean.PM2.5.Concentration, COUNTY, Site.Name) 

data_no2 <- data_NO2 %>%
  select (Date, daily.no2 = Daily.Max.1.hour.NO2.Concentration, COUNTY, Site.Name)  
data_so2 <- data_SO2 %>%
  select (Date, daily.so2 = Daily.Max.1.hour.SO2.Concentration, COUNTY, Site.Name) 
data_co <- data_CO %>%
  select (Date, daily.co = Daily.Max.8.hour.CO.Concentration, COUNTY, Site.Name) 
data_o3 <- data_O3 %>%
  select (Date, daily.o3 = Daily.Max.8.hour.Ozone.Concentration, COUNTY, Site.Name)

Since SO2 and NO2 is measured by ppb, which is different from the unit of CO and O3 (ppm) I transform the unit of SO2 and NO2 from ppb to ppm by dividing the value by 1000.

data_so2$daily.so2 <-  data_so2$daily.so2/1000
data_no2$daily.no2 <-  data_no2$daily.no2/1000

Merge all the data into one dataset using full_join.

data_emission <- full_join(data_pm2.5, data_co, by = c( "Date", "COUNTY", "Site.Name" ))

Skewness

From numerical value visualization, I found that daily.pm.2.5 (outcome) and daily.so2 are right skewed, with so2 data skewed more. So let’s look more into daily.so2.

train_data_so2_conc <-
train_data %>%
  mutate (
    so2 = case_when(
    daily.so2 == 0 ~ "clean",
    daily.so2 > 0 & daily.so2 <= 0.002 ~ "low",
    daily.so2 > 0.002 & daily.so2 <= 0.004 ~ "Mid",
    daily.so2 > 0.004 & daily.so2 <= 0.006 ~ "High",
    daily.so2 > 0.006 ~ "SupHigh",)
    ) # %>%
  #mutate (so2, fct_infreq(so2))
head (train_data_so2_conc)
train_data_so2_conc %>%

  • Step 3. Data Pre-processing

Deal with skewness

train_data2 <- 
  train_data %>%
    mutate(daily.so2 = log (daily.so2+1)) %>%
    mutate(daily.pm2.5 = log (daily.pm2.5 +1))
## Warning in log(daily.pm2.5 + 1): NaNs produced
test_data2 <- 
  test_data %>%
    mutate(daily.so2 = log (daily.so2+1) ) %>%
    mutate(daily.pm2.5 = log (daily.pm2.5))


train_data2 %>%
  select (daily.so2, daily.pm2.5) %>%
  gather (var, val) %>%
  ggplot (aes(val)) +
    geom_histogram (bins = 50) +
    facet_wrap(~var, scales = "free", ncol = 3)
## Warning: Removed 1 rows containing non-finite values (stat_bin).

Then, build the recipe, transform nominal data into dummies, and scale all the vairable in order to compare.

# Build a receipt
# install.packages("recipes")
require (recipes)
rcp <- 
  recipe (daily.pm2.5 ~ . , train_data2) %>%
    step_dummy(all_nominal(), -all_outcomes()) %>%
    # Normalize Scale
    step_range (all_numeric()) %>%
    prep()

# Apply the recipe to the training and test data
train_data3 <- bake(rcp,train_data2)
test_data3 <- bake(rcp,test_data2) 

head(train_data3)

  • Step 4. Cross-Validation

Set cross-validation settings as an object that can be easily applied across different machine learning applications Use K-fold cross-validation method with 5 subsets.

# set seed for replication
set.seed (1988)
# randomly dividing the data into 5 groups
folds <- 
  createFolds (train_data3$daily.pm2.5, k = 5)

# check the length of each fold
sapply(folds,length)
## Fold1 Fold2 Fold3 Fold4 Fold5 
##   112   114   114   116   113
control_conditions <-
  trainControl(
    method = "cv",
    index = folds
    )

  • Step 5. Build Model

    1. Linear Regression
mod_lm <-
  train (
    daily.pm2.5 ~ . , 
    data = train_data3, 
    method = "lm",
    metric = "RMSE",
    # cross validation conditions
    trControl = control_conditions
  )

    trControl = control_conditions
    )

3. Rank of Air Pollution of Different Counties in 2018

  • Which County is the most polluted in 2018?
data_emission_county <- 
  data_emission %>%
  select (Date, daily.pm2.5, COUNTY) %>%
  group_by (COUNTY) %>%
  na.omit (.) %>%
  summarise (mean_daily_pm2.5 = mean(daily.pm2.5), var_daily_pm2.5 = var(daily.pm2.5) ) %>%
  arrange(desc(mean_daily_pm2.5)) %>%
  top_n(10)
## Selecting by var_daily_pm2.5
data_emission_county
